`useFieldArray` initializes the array as soon as it mounts, so the only way to prevent `once: []` from appearing is to avoid mounting it until that key already exists (or until you explicitly decide to allow it).

Two practical options:

Option 1: Gate the `FieldArray` on the key existing
```ts
const hasActivePresets =
  amountPresetsByFrequency &&
  Object.prototype.hasOwnProperty.call(amountPresetsByFrequency, activeFrequency);

{amountPresetsPath && activeFrequency && hasActivePresets ? (
  <FieldArray key={amountPresetsPath} name={amountPresetsPath}>
    ...
  </FieldArray>
) : null}
```
This keeps RHF from creating `once: []` until the data already contains that key.

Option 2: Gate on “loaded presets” with a local flag
```ts
const [presetsReady, setPresetsReady] = useState(false);

useEffect(() => {
  if (amountPresetsByFrequency && Object.keys(amountPresetsByFrequency).length > 0) {
    setPresetsReady(true);
  }
}, [amountPresetsByFrequency]);

{amountPresetsPath && activeFrequency && presetsReady ? (
  <FieldArray key={amountPresetsPath} name={amountPresetsPath}>
    ...
  </FieldArray>
) : null}
```
This still allows initialization later, but only after the config actually changes.

If you want, I can wire one of these into `src/pages/ActionPages/pages/ActionPagesBuilder/Designer/Finance/Amounts/Amounts.tsx`.

